segments.text: One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
One, two, three.
Say something.
Testing.
Testing.
This is Monday, the 28th of August.
Sitting in a nice, quiet living room at Jim Ray's house, getting ready to chat with him about his experiences here, being the man in charge of all of the scenery.
Let's see, now I should say Gene and not Eugene.
That's fine, either way.
But most people call you Gene?
Most people call me Gene, yes.
To introduce yourself to anyone who may listen to this tape or read a transcription that didn't know you, describe your background before you got to A&M.
Where'd you grow up, what'd your family do, went to high school, college, where'd you work and all in the service before you got here?
I was born east of Abilene, Texas, between Abilene and Albany, and my father was a farmer.
My mother taught school at a little two-room school at Hamby, Texas.
When I was, after school when I was nine, we moved to Leveland, Texas.
My dad bought a hatchery and feed store there and we moved out to the flatlands and graduated from Leveland High School in 1955 and went to Texas Tech and
majored in horticulture and park administration and graduated in 1960 and came back to Level End in a small business.
and was in that for, it was a small nursery and greenhouse operation until 1963 and decided that the town was too small and people didn't,
understand that I was grown and I had some information and that my services weren't free.
And so we moved to Oklahoma City and I went to work for Higdon's nursery and greenhouse operation.
I was managing some greenhouses, about an acre of greenhouses, and did a little landscape design work.
That's when I renewed my acquaintance with Bob Rucker.
Bob came in, he was back, Bob was my landscape design prof at Tech and had gone back to the University of Oklahoma and I guess it was maybe the fall of 1959, somewhere along in there.
And he was at Tech about three years and at any rate, he came in

the governor, Henry Bellman, had asked him to more or less be in charge of the work Oklahoma exhibited at the New York World's Fair, which was depicting the green area of Oklahoma, the water and everything like this.
He came in hunting redbud trees, state tree of Oklahoma.
And we hadn't seen each other in a number of years.
And so, you know, I knew he was down there and
things, this was long in the fall of 1963 and long in the spring, he came back in and that was an early summer actually because that

had taken him away from his job at OU and he said how would you like to leave this place and I said fine because at that point in time my 45 hour a week job had gone to seven days a week candle can't and it was
a lot of long hours, and I said fine, where's the door?
And so that's how I got into the campus grounds, landscape grounds business.
And I went down as Bob's assistant supervisor in the summer of 1964.

and I've often kind of kiddingly said that it was the New York World's Fair that got me into this and which it actually was I guess but and I stayed at Oklahoma until Bob came down here in 1968 and I took his job and then
Stayed there until early 1973, and then came to work down here on March 1, 1973.
Summarize briefly your responsibilities at OU.
My responsibility at OU was basically what they were here.

I was in charge of all the landscaping grounds, a few other things, but primarily all the grounds, everything outside basically, and the routine maintenance, the design and implementation of new landscapes around buildings, and this type of thing.
describe the process here.
How did they contact you, or you them?
How did the employment come about?
Well, I had got a call.
Well, when Bob came down here in 1968, he came down here to a garden club.
He was very involved in national garden clubs.
And he came back and said, would you like to go to A&M?

in 1968 and I said no I'm happy here you know and when he had mentioned that when in fact I think they were really after him which that in fact came about but then in in I guess in December yeah it must have been in December of
of uh 73 yeah 72 ray smith who was director of personnel at that point in time called me and asked me if i would be interested in coming down to interview and i said yeah i might you know uh
And although I was quite happy at OU, it had been very lean on salary increases and all, and so I decided it might be a good thing I could come down and visit Rucker and all like that.
So he said, well, you can come down during Christmas break.
And I said, what Christmas break?
I said, we get Christmas Eve afternoon and Christmas.
But anyway, I had plenty of vacation time, so I came down and interviewed and visited with them.

Bob and he carried me around and then took me up to meet Tom Cherry who was his boss and ultimately my boss and we became, we had a very good connection at that point in time and ultimately had a very good working relationship but I'm very fond of both Bob Rucker and Tom Cherry.
As far as you then indicate

they contacted you you didn't yes no i didn't apply do you have any idea whether you were the only person they were i have no idea never asked who uh who who was involved in the interview visit who'd you meet um basically bob rucker and tom cherry uh did they sit down together and they talked to you separately uh separately and then together um
I came and visited with Bob, and he took me around campus and then up to the Koch building in Tom's office.
And we sat down and probably visited for about an hour.
And finally, Mr. Cherry said, what makes you think you can come down here and handle this?
And I said, well, it might be we could both learn something, you know, because me being from Texas Tech and all.
And we got along great.

did did they give you a comparatively clear understanding of what they were looking for what what did they want done they they wanted someone basically to assist bob and i came as assistant landscape architect and in charge of basically all the all the maintenance operations and i had some input into the design and at that point in time we were just
formulating

I would guess I would call it a site development aspect where as a project, let's say a major building project went through facilities planning and construction, there would be a certain amount of money that was set aside for site work, landscape and irrigation.
And at that point in time we decided that if we were going to have a viable landscape, we had to irrigate it.
So therefore the two went hand in glove.

because if if uh if we were going to have something green we had to water it and that started we had a few irrigation systems on campus but that really started the growth of all of our landscape irrigation systems simply because there are times like this summer that if you don't water it you're not going to have it do you remember asking them any questions
that where you got an answer that was disappointing to you?
No, really.
We talked about a number of things, how it would work.
One of the things that, and I'll be real frank, what appealed to me was that the grounds area was in the final stage of separation from the physical plant.
At OU, I had worked under the director of physical plant, which

it will work both ways there are times when it works better and this basically allowed direct access to the administration without having to go through a director of physical plant who is normally an engineer there's nothing wrong with engineers but they're interested in buildings and structures and and utilities and things like this and they're not too keen
on the green things and the aesthetic part of a campus.
That's what I've generally found.
Did they give you a comparatively clear definition of what your responsibility is going to be relative to working with Bob Rucker?

not really they basically they said that I would be his assistant and that you see it at that time Bob I believe was also head of he was director of grounds landscape architect and head of horticulture floriculture the academic side and which that that was a pretty good load and so basically they wanted me to
to handle the maintenance end of it and the implementation part as we got into some new buildings and site work, this kind of thing.
What promises did they make or what commitments did they make?
Nothing other than I would be making about a third to 50% more than what I was making at OU.
All right, now that's out.
This is the only money question I'm going to ask.
What was the beginning salary?
I came here at $15,000 a year.
I was making $10,000 at OU.
And this is 1973?
Let's see.
In these conversations, interviews or just plain conversations, the fact that you had gone to Tech, did that appear to be an advantage or a disadvantage?
No.
It was a...
It was a point of discussion a little bit between Mr. Cherry and myself.
He was kidding me quite a bit, you know, about a little bit, and it was all, I enjoyed that part of it.
That was great.
Was he an A&M undergraduate?
I don't remember where he went to school, but I never thought of him as an
You know, I think he went to Sam.
I believe you're right.
I'm almost positive he did.
But, no, he and I just, I don't know, we, you know, you get, and I think we both got the feeling, you know, we just both hit it off very nicely.
Describe the move down here.
Well, I...
The family and the meetings and everything.
I left, it was on Friday, Friday evening, it was like
3rd of January, something like this.
But I remember it was on a Friday because I'd come down on Thursday.
And so I had called my wife and told her that it was very interesting and we had some talking to do, you know, when I got back.
And there was a major cold spell coming down.
And I got iced in at Fort Worth going back.
And something told me I better get up the next morning and try to get home.
And it took me eight hours to drive from Fort Worth to Norman.
And the further I got, the more snow.
I mean, there were cars off the road, you know, and it was,
Oh, 20, 25 miles an hour, maybe.
And I got home, and we had like 15 inches of snow on the ground.
But anyway, we sat down and talked about it.
And of course, we have three children.
We have the oldest, Randy.
He was in eighth grade.
Melissa was in probably the fifth grade.
And Doug was probably second grade, maybe.
And so we decided, okay, this is too good an opportunity to pass up.
So we talked to the kids and Randy says, bye, I'm staying here.
You know, I like it here.
I don't want to move.
So we decided that maybe we could afford a four bedroom house.
And at that point in time, he and Douglas would not have to share a room because it was like the odd couple, basically.
because Randy is always neat and exact, I mean, everything in its place, and Douglas is, you know, the floor is a storage facility, that kind of thing.
And so that kind of changed his mind a little bit.
So anyway, we came down and
I called Bob and told him that I would accept the job.
And so then we made a couple of trips, three trips down, house hunting and all that, put our house on the market.
And there were only three or four four-bedroom houses in Bryan and College Station for sale.
This happened to be one of them.
Was this a new house?

No, this was about 18 months old, and the folks, the family were military, and he'd come back to school for a little bit and was leaving, and we looked at it, and Janet didn't like the kitchen, and then we looked and looked and looked, and

finally came back to that that it was a very small kitchen and but we decided we wouldn't handle it and so we I guess our house sold probably two days before we moved you know and I'd gotten calls from

one or two of the banks said you know if you need if you need a loan before you sell your house not a problem you know and it was a very um very warm type reception and all and so we moved and uh down here the last couple of days of february and uh and i went to work first march

describe getting settled in first of all in the community the schools the community the neighbors what was it like for a newcomer to College Station it wasn't very bad the Janet joined the newcomers group and of course the kids moved and and they got right in school and they didn't have they didn't have a problem
blending in.

Of course, Randy was right close to the high school, and Melissa was going, I think she finished up at South Knoll, and Doug was going to South Knoll, and then the next year she went to, I guess, the middle school then.
On that point, did you have any impression of the quality of the Indian Missile Aid schools with the Norman schools at that time?

Um fairly similar the particularly the two the two younger ones had the grade school they were in was the open open classroom concept and that that was the primary difference I think it's just that they were used to that rather than you know very well delineated classrooms but really didn't didn't have any in terms of quality
I don't know that we had any quality differential there at all.
We had good schools in Norman, and kids seemed to, they didn't have to do any catch-up at all.
If anything, they might have been a little bit ahead in places.
All right, now describe getting settled in on the campus.
Okay.
Where were you quartered, and who, staff did you work with, and so forth?

We had at that point in time only a couple of supervisory staff, and we were headquartered at what was then the grounds maintenance quarters on Old College at Hensel Park, a couple of quonset huts that were quite old, and had probably about 50 workers.
had a couple of supervisory staff, and I never will forget, of course, College Avenue was, as it is now, is busy thoroughfare.
And we, I found out, didn't have a whole lot of equipment.
I had some tractor-operated mowers, and I think we had two or three small riding mowers.
And I remember thinking, after a

got to work and the people were going out and there were those three little riding mowers going out at eight o'clock in the morning and competing with that vehicular traffic on college avenue and just scared the liver out of me you know it just you know just hazards everywhere just but you know we got by that and then ultimately probably about

five or six months later we wound up with a portion of the basement of the old hospital building that we used as as a work area for the smaller equipment and things like this so we didn't have to road it back and forth you know when and got rid of a lot of the uh the hazard of the on that level how did
I'm assuming the two institutions were similar in size and enrollment and so forth then.
Probably so.
How did the workforce here and equipment compare with what you left at OU?
It was not as good here.
because I had worked on equipment up there and had gotten it up to what I would consider a decent level.
And that's one of the things Mr. Cherry was very active in.
He, you know, I would see a need and talk to Bob and either he or I would talk to Mr. Cherry and Tom found

two or three batches of money that I'm not sure where he got it but I didn't worry about that at the time and so we could we could purchase needed equipment ranging from oh gosh a small motor grader to
riding type mowers, and just a whole gamut of different types of equipment that we needed.
And that, we got the first batch of equipment was probably in the summer of 73 and then in the fall of 73, another batch of equipment.
So we were catching up in a hurry, you know.
And then, by then, I was melded into the budget thing.
Of course, in September of 73 is when Bob started having knee problems.
And I think he just had surgery at that point in time on his good leg.
And the doctors told him that he was going to have to make a choice, that he couldn't
Both jobs were too demanding, particularly on his good leg, and that he really needed to give one of the jobs up.
And so he decided that he would go to the academic side.
And then I went over with Mr. Cherry and met with Dr. Williams.
and about my assuming the job of Director of Grounds Maintenance.
And we talked for a while.
And there had been, I think, some
consternation with the academic landscape architecture folks about Bob being called landscape architect.
Well, he was.
I mean, he's a very qualified landscape architect.
But the fact that he wasn't in the academic side and this kind of thing, I think, I don't know.
And Dr. Williams says, well, you'll be director of grounds, but you won't be landscape architect.
You won't be titled landscape architect.
Yeah, that's what it was.
And I said, well, you know, that's not a problem.
I know what I am, and I know what I can do and that kind of thing.

And it went that way for several years before it was changed to director of grounds landscape architect again, you know, but, but I remember that real, real clearly, you know, that that was, and I, I, uh, I don't know whether I looked puzzled or not.
And later Mr. Cherry said, well, there's a little, little bit of problem there with some of the academic folks and just passed it off on, you know, like that, like Tom would do.
In that and other sessions,
What did you sense to be the working relationship between Tom Cherry and Jack Williams?
I sensed that it was good.
I didn't sense any kind of... Mutual trust and respect?
Yeah, I think so.
They seemed to have a very good working relationship.
I know that's great.
And I was only with both of them.
probably a half a dozen times.
Describe Tom Cherry as a human being, and then as a supervisor.
He was, in my opinion, one of the more understanding people that I've met.
Tom was extremely knowledgeable in the finance, the budget works, and all like this.
And I know I, when I became director of Grounds,
Well, going back to mid-summer of 1973, that's when we were setting up, we set up a landscape construction section and irrigation, a landscape maintenance section, and a roads and pavement section.

found supervisors for each each of those areas and the landscape construction section was going to handle all of the new construction and maintain the install and maintain irrigation systems this kind of thing and as a part of that we were set up with a local account that's something that had never been done with the ground theory and and Mr. Cherry and Clark Diebel
set the thing up, and Bob says, okay, you handle the outside, I'll take care of all this.
Well, I didn't have an idea, man of the moon, how the local account worked.
And when the change made, it was made rather quickly, and we were still tied to the physical plant with an accountant over in their accounting area, named Marie L.
And so BC Hurt, who was my number one guy, had been, BC had been here for like 35 years or so.
H-E-R-T. H-U-R-T. H-U-R-T Hurt.
Yeah, BC.
He had no name, just initials, BC.
And in December
And we'd been working out of a local account, you know, and all like this.
And I got a call in December, early December of, no, just before Christmas of 73.
And I got a call from Marie.
And she said, sir, you need to come over here.
So I went over there.
She said, you've got a problem.
You're $60,000 in the red.
And I thought, oh, geez.
And so it was probably a day or two before Christmas break.
I spent the most miserable Christmas break I have ever spent in all my life, wondering why I'd ever come down here.
And my wife still doesn't know.
I've never said anything.
And I made up my mind.
that I needed to go talk to Tom Cherry.
So first day back I called and I said, Mr. Cherry, I need to come talk to you.
I've got a problem.
Went up and I laid it all out and he said, yeah, you've got a problem.
I thought, oh, man.

and he said you need somebody to mind your business and so he called downstairs and got Clark Diebel brought him up and they set some things up and then he called I guess Logan Council was director of physical plant at that point in time yeah and

the upshot was they moved Marie Allen over physically to us and Clark set up some he set us up on how to handle the local account and you know and once I got into it it was pretty simple I just didn't know that if you spin it you had to make it kind of thing and so by uh between B.C.
Hurt and Bill Vittlepill who was
He was working half-time.
He was half-time horticulture, half-time grounds, and ultimately came over full-time the next year.
But between the three or four of us, we were out of the red by March of 74, you know, learned a valuable lesson.
But like I say, Tom Cherry didn't faze him, you know.
He just said, you need somebody to mind your business, you know.
Now, in hindsight, was that whole matter handled appropriately?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, I figured I was going to be fired, frankly, because, I mean, $60,000, you know.
Clark Diebel, describe him.
Clark was one of the more helpful guys.
I mean, any time I needed a problem solved or had a problem with money or accounts or
anything like that, I could always call Clark.
And he had an answer.
He always had an answer.
